2 (iv) reduces administrative burdens and costs and drives funding toward classroom instruction;
3 (v) allows for parental choice within an expanded public education system;
4 (vi) eliminates the need for tuition payments between school districts;
5 (vii) minimizes property tax impacts related to the reappraisal cycle; and
6 (viii) incorporates free market principles where appropriate and rewards school districts based on
7 student academic growth, achievement, and proficiency rather than head counts and seat time; and
